Since 1940, natural successional processes have gov- erned stand development. Periodic insect infestations,
wind, lightning, and occasional ice storms are the most common forms of disturbance.

Most of Indiana was deforested by the early 1900s, but afforestation has occurred in much of central and southern Indiana after abandonment of marginally productive agricultural land. Timber harvests have not occurred in the source area of the flux tower recently except in one small seed-tree area. Wind, lightning, and ice storms are the most common types of natural disturbances. Fires occur oc- casionally but are uncommon and never widespread

Our experiment followed the methods of the Interna- tional Tundra Experiment using open-top chambers (OTC) as a passive warming device to generate an artificially warmed environment. The OTCs were hex- agonal with sloping sides constructed of 3-mm thick translucent Plexiglas (Marion et al. 1997). This material has high solar transmittance in visible wavelengths (about 90%) and low transmittance in the infrared (heat) range (<5%). The chambers were 60 cm high and the distance between parallel sides were 115 cm at the base and 60 cm apart at the top. Each OTC had an open-top area of 1.06 m2 and covered a ground area of 2.45 m2. In March 2005, we installed five OTCs be- neath the 60-year spruce plantation and five OTCs in adjacent forest openings, respectively (in total, ten chambers). Moreover, at each site, a control plot (80 · 80 cm; 0.64 m2) was also established in the vicinity of each OTC; thus, in total, ten control plots were set up. It was expected that all of the selected plots were similar in microhabitat characteristics, with the exception of light environments
